________________
Exploring Space: Principles for Effective Innovation Leadership
Herbert von Karajan once said that the chief task of the conductor is to know when to do nothing and let the orchestra play. Like every good conductor, Karajan was convinced that “it” would play by itself, once the musicians knew what to do. In this sense, Karajan was an enabler; someone who focused not on owning the success all by himself, but on bringing the team forward. This is the hallmark of great leadership: bringing the best out of people and thereby build something that is bigger than the sum of the individual contributions.
As your company is entering the field of exponential innovation, this basic principle remains intact. The difference is however, that instead of focusing on enabling productivity you will need to set your mind on enabling creativity within your coworkers. This chapter is about exploring the space that you hopefully setup while working through our chapter on “Creating Space”.
It is one thing to enable creativity in your workforce, it is quite another to manage the resulting multitude of ideas and approaches into a solution that can create value for you, your organization and society at large.
The problem with creativity is that it is highly individualistic, and so when working in teams or on large projects you will ultimately face the problem that the creative solutions that your colleagues are pursuing will not readily work in your organization.
But how can you make sure, that all the creative solutions that your employees are developing, will ultimately benefit the company? In our work we have developed the following ledership principles that will help you pursue this goal:

Principle one: Honor good ideas and celebrate the death of not so good ones.
Probably the most intuitive way to promote the new is by celebrating those who have good ideas. This can be done in several ways:
1. Create a culture of giving credit to everyone who participates in a project. Giving credit is a powerful tool for increasing creativity, because the draw of seeing one’s name on a publication next to a company logo, speaks to the inner narcissist in many of us. We are simply proud of our accomplishments and so are the many people who work with us. The problem with some approaches to giving credit is, that they automatically include those at the top of the organizational pyramid, no matter how much they participated in the creative process. Take for instance the conventions in academia, where many professors, advisors, principle investigators or other senior personel get created in every publication that leaves their lab, group or even department. To be fair, in many cases, they are not listed as principle author (the first author to be named), but the practise is widespread nevertheless. As a leader in a business environment, this might mean to reflect on whether it should only be your name on the article in the corporate communication journal, or not also the name of your assistant who has put in fleshing out the backbone of your ideas. Perhaps you will come to conclusion, that the article should be published under the name of your co-worker altogether, because it was her idea and she put in most of the work. The rule of thumb that we follow is this: the main or sole author of a text, video, or speech is the person crafting the actual message and delivering it. If the ideas in a text are by someone else, they should be prominently referenced, for instance by saying “it was Bill Gates who first remarked, that...” This means that by simply provding an idea and a list of arguments or a strucuture for a text, one cannot become a main author. Putting in the work does, however.


Intrapreneurship
Business processes as a service (for instance distribution)
Competition of ideas around funds and resources (Google model)
R&D needs commitment by owner
Present knowledge with low barriers of entry
Open mode, closed mode
A better word for protocol
How do you know your vision? How do you communicate it? How can you thereby channel the creativity of everyone on your team?


Step 1: Take the very best
Step 2: Define the direction
Step 3: Allow people to become virtuosos in their field, provide tools (people have growth and self-actualization needs)
Step 4: Communicate big picture, vision align everyone


