## Decentralization 101

### Metadata

```yaml
title: Decentralization 101
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2019-06-07T10:19:03.508Z
modified: 2022-02-10T14:49:34.159Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/Decentralization 101
id: 1qJt0zRDRQyYFzHDXrQaIwyuoV6EvRIESamj83LpmmVI
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1qJt0zRDRQyYFzHDXrQaIwyuoV6EvRIESamj83LpmmVI/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

The document explores the transformative power of decentralization and blockchain technology, illustrating how decentralized networks enhance information flow and reduce asymmetry compared to centralized systems. It explains the role of blockchain in ensuring data integrity and transparency, with applications in cryptocurrencies, asset ownership, and smart contracts. The text highlights the potential societal impacts, such as increased efficiency, innovation, and reduced barriers to entry. It emphasizes the need for creativity and innovation in value creation, suggesting that traditional business models may become obsolete in favor of more collaborative and technology-driven approaches.

**Key Concepts:**

- Decentralized vs. centralized networks
- Blockchain technology and information integrity
- Applications of blockchain: cryptocurrencies, smart contracts
- Societal impacts of decentralization: efficiency, innovation
- Challenges to traditional business models
- Importance of creativity and innovation
- Role of technology in societal development

### Full Content

﻿Decentralization 101
1. How I learnt of the transformative power of technology and imagining alternative realities
2. Demonstration of information flow and efficiency in three types of networks.
   1. In a centralized network all traffic runs through a central node which limits the bandwidth of information that can be processed.
   2. If all nodes of a network are connected to their nearest neighbours, the bandwidth increases, because traffic can be routed via the shortest or least used route.
   3. A network in which all nodes are connected to every other node are super fast, with high bandwidth but difficult to scale.
3. Demonstration of information asymmetry in centralized vs. decentralized networks
   1. Centralized networks allow for an asymmetry in information distribution (one node can have more or better information than other nodes; or even worse censorship can occur; or information can be falsified)
   2. Decentralized networks allow for an even distribution of information and make censorship impossible
4. But how do we guarantee in decentralized networks that all nodes have the same information available?
   1. This is where blockchain comes into play!
   2. All changes to information on the network will be broadcast to all nodes of the network
   3. A mathematical riddle that is difficult to solve secures the authenticity of the new information. Its correctness can be verified by all nodes very easily, however
   4. Every node stores the exact and correct history of all transaction, therefore has access to all available and verified information.
5. Examples for blockchain-enabled applications
   1. Cryptocurrencies
   2. Efficient accounting for intra-organizations and inter-organization transactions
   3. Ownership transfer of digital and physical assets
6. Instead of only distributing data or information via such a blockchain system, we can also use it to distribute computer programs (smart contracts), run them and store their output. What can be done with that?
   1. Smart contracts can create and manage tokens, which can represent all sorts of assets:
      1. Intellectual property rights (can be licensed)
      2. Real world assets such as real estate, container ships (can have shared ownership and easy transfer of shares or proceeds via cryptocurrencies)
      3. Financing of startups
      4. Bonds
      5. Insurance
   2. Tokens can be used together with game theory approach to create market places for all sorts of tangible and intangible assets. The smart contracts will model individual incentives for each market player.
      1. Reward systems such as frequent flyer programs
      2. Data Marketplace for machine learning
      3. Modeling work contracts, organization equity and remuneration systems in ad-hoc working groups
7. Some reflections on what that means for our societies:
   1. Evenly distributed information makes man in the middle value generation superfluous
   2. Increase of efficiency lowers prices and margins
   3. Fast distribution of innovation lowers barrier of entry for everyone
8. Value creation will be difficult to achieve with traditional business models where I sell a service or product with a markup from my production or acquisition cost.
9. Value creation will increasingly depend on innovation, which in turn necessitates increases in creativity everywhere and with everyone. 
10. Tech drives this development but of course we need to develop and use it in our favor and according to our goals. So in a first step we need to understand what we want and then involve as many creative minds as possible. This is why we founded Sonophilia.


---

## European Renaissance Text

### Metadata

```yaml
title: European Renaissance Text
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2021-12-30T12:31:36.757Z
modified: 2022-01-03T16:41:00.783Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/European Renaissance Text
id: 1R66bwk6b-alM1xeos8sxDHh7jqpYU6UgE1JeSpZ0Y2E
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1R66bwk6b-alM1xeos8sxDHh7jqpYU6UgE1JeSpZ0Y2E/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

The document discusses the ambitious project of completing Beethoven's unfinished 10th Symphony using AI, initiated by Deutsche Telekom as a tribute to Beethoven. The project, Beethoven X, faced criticism from cultural conservatives who viewed AI's involvement in creativity as sacrilegious, yet it was widely celebrated by audiences and media. The authors argue for a human-centric Renaissance where AI democratizes creativity, allowing more people to engage in artistic and innovative endeavors. They emphasize the potential of AI to enhance human creativity and call for a shift in mindset to embrace technology as a tool for creative empowerment. The document also highlights the need for courage and experimentation in integrating AI into creative processes, advocating for an 'Age of Creativity' where human-machine collaboration flourishes.

**Key Concepts:**

- AI in creative processes
- Beethoven X project
- Democratizing creativity
- Human-machine collaboration
- Cultural conservatism vs. innovation
- Potential of AI to enhance creativity
- Age of Creativity

### Full Content

﻿Our Ode to Creativity
Seda and Matthias Röder






In 2019 Michael Schuld of Deutsche Telekom, asked whether an AI could be built to finish Beethoven’s 10th Symphony – a revolutionary  homage and a birthday gift to Beethoven by the Bonn-based company bringing together technology, arts and communications. In this piece we reflect on the reactions of recipients from different milieus. Although general audiences embrace the endeavor, cultural conservatives argue to exclude AI from entering the genius-oriented realm of creativityBeethoven AI is a tool - like printing in the 15th century. In this short essay we make the case on how to put AI-supported Art to use for a human-centric Renaissance.
 
------------------------


Finishing Beethoven's 10th Symphony with AI support would be monumentally complex - we knew right away. It is so for two reasons. First, there exist only a very small number of sketches for the symphony and they are for the most part in a fragmentary state. Therefore understanding Beethoven’s intentions for this 10th symphony is difficult. Second, honoring what Beethoven had already written, but keeping in mind his incredible versatility in working with musical material, required a very flexible and unique kind of AI that did not yet exist. As we started the project however, a third complexity emerged to overtrump all others. Beethoven was seen as one of the pinnacles of human creativity and we were receiving criticism even before one tone was played: How could we even dare to create music with an AI that could compare with Beethoven’s music? 


Two years later, in October 2021, Beethoven X – The AI Project was premiered, at Deutsche Telekom’s headquarters in Bonn. Thousands of people around the world followed the live-stream along with hundreds in the audience. Not one person in the crowd was able to tell where exactly the sketches of Beethoven ended and where the music of the AI took over. Standing ovations filled the hall  for many minutes… Music aficionados, technology enthusiasts and distinguished media outlets such as CNN, BBC, BILD and many more from around the globe seemed to love the result, while the album entered the German pop charts.


Nonetheless, following the premiere, a heated discussion broke out.The conservative feuilletonists and hard-core traditionalists labeled Beethoven X as “sacrilege” and were particularly bitter in their judgement. Going over the music motif by motif, they discussed whether our AI matched  Beethoven’s “genius” music, or whether it was just an unemotional imitation of the original – often confusing and criticizing the original fragments with music produced by the AI. The discussion however showed striking similarities to the criticism that others have received for creating their completion of Beethoven’s 10th symphony. That’s when we realized that the whole debate was clearly not about the music itself nor about the capabilities of the technology, but it was about excluding AI (and sometimes even humans) from entering the genius-oriented realm of creativity. 
But Beethoven X heralds a future where there are no barriers of entry into the ivory tower of arts. It foreshadows a new kind of Renaissance that is all about democratizing creativity for all rather than making it a privilege for a few. Most importantly, Beethoven X aspires to be part of a future where humans and machines interact productively so that more people can harness the benefits of technological tools to unleash creativity, to self-actualize and to contribute to humanity.Technologies are advancing rapidly. Therefore, unleashing their potential for the greater good is, quite frankly, a pressing matter. We should, perhaps, be maximizing the creative potential in the world with much more urgency. Consider this: according to the numbers compiled by the Austrian Statistics Agency, we have only 0.02% of the entire world population working in any innovation and creativity-related field — R&D, environment, food, societal innovation, arts… you name it!


But can it truly be that only 2 out of 10,000 people are actually creative? Can it truly be that only 2 out of 10,000 people can contribute to innovation or to arts? Of course not!


We live in a world obsessed with not wasting resources, yet when it comes to human potential, we seem somewhat complacent. Considering our world’s current situation, we need all the help we can get to start asking different kinds of questions and exploring new pathways where old ones are failing. That is precisely where the power of human-machine interaction lies.


Our Beethoven AI gave us options… Options we could never have produced in such a timeframe. In so doing, it maximized our creativity. The options it so effortlessly produced were threefold. First, they expanded our horizons in that AI didn’t care about our conventions, taboos, or rules. Second, they gave us freedom, putting us in the driver’s seat with an amazing array of choices. Finally, they saved us tons of time which we could spend focusing on and learning about things that really matter. All of that is indeed “human” music to our ears.


If an AI can help humans be more creative, more “human” even, the question remains: why are we not employing this technology much more widely to address and solve other problems, too?
Perhaps the answer is that our age lacks courage. Business-as-usual mentality and fearing failure is omnipresent in our organisations. Many are reluctant to experiment with AI within the context of creativity. Or maybe the fear lies in the idea of a machine becoming a “more creative individual,” as if we were in competition.


Humans are not computers, nor should they be treated as such. Unfortunately, this is still the case; just observe your child’s homework sheet, and you’ll immediately know what we’re talking about. Our systems should be focusing more on raising first-class creative and collaborative thinkers, learners and inventors, rather than programming what are essentially second-class calculators.


Let’s accept the reality: Humans are generally not very good at reproducing Knowledge 101. Our memory capabilities and speed of data-processing are simply flawed in comparison with machines, but we excel at other things, particularly at empathy and creativity. We are also extremely good at unleashing the potential of all sorts of tools around us: We invent tools to improve the lives of people we’ve never even met. We utilize tools all the time to inspire and connect with each other. Our Beethoven AI is one of them.


This is a turning point in history. Instead of asking whether someone is “allowed” to use AI in the creative process or to emulate the style of a creative superstar, we should be instilling the right mindset and the joy of experimentation to awaken the creative superstar inherent in everyone. It is high time we stop putting people into boxes only to later instruct them to think outside of the box!


As the debates and reflections around our Beethoven experiment unfold, we must begin acting on that promise.


Our world is slowly coming out of the Industrial Age, but what’s next is not the age of technology, digitalization, or transhumanism.


It’s the Age of Creativity!




About Matthias Röder


Dr. Matthias Röder is an award-winning music and technology strategist. He is Co-Founder and Managing Partner at The Mindshift, a consultancy on creative leadership and innovation strategy. Matthias currently serves as a board member of the Karajan Foundation and is the Managing Director of the Eliette and Herbert von Karajan Institute. He is also a member of the board of trustees of the Mozarteum Foundation. In 2017, Matthias founded the Karajan Music Tech Conference, a cross-industry event to promote breakthrough technologies in music, media and audio. He is also the founder of the Classical Music Hack Day series which he launched in 2013. Together with his wife, Seda Röder, Matthias co-founded the Sonophilia Foundation, a non-profit that promotes a scientific approach to creativity. Matthias has won numerous prizes and accolades for his work, including most recently, the “Game Changer” Award of the Chamber of Commerce Salzburg. He is a sought-after speaker and lecturer who has taught at Harvard University, the Change & Innovation Management Program at University of St. Gall, and Salzburg University. He holds a PhD in music from Harvard University and is an alumnus of the Mozarteum University Salzburg.


Royalty-Free Image (click link to full version)


  

‪2,362px x 3,539‬px
https://drive.google.com/file/d/0Bx1CFeMjUjlmWHZVN1AtUEx1M00/view?usp=sharing&resourcekey=0-XP3OQdqU5Im68lj4Q_djkA
Photo Credit: "Foto HUBERT AUER Salzburg"


About Seda Röder


Seda Röder, aka “the piano hacker”, is an author, entrepreneur and philanthropist devoted to cultivating creativity in society and organisations. She is a sought-after speaker, consultant to DAX listed companies and the founder of the Sonophilia Foundation; a non-profit organization dedicated to advancing the scientific research of creativity and critical thinking. Seda is Co-Founder and Managing Partner at The Mindshift, a consultancy on creative technologies and change leadership. Furthermore, Seda is a fellow and a member of the Salzburg Global Seminar Corporate Governance Forum, angel investor and network partner at the European startup accelerator Silicon Castles. In 2018 Seda received the Game Changer Award at the Austrian Chamber of Commerce for her business merits. Before relocating to Europe, Seda taught music performance, theory and history at Harvard University and Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) as an Associate and Affiliated Artist.
