## 2021-05-13_Fair Saturday

### Metadata

```yaml
title: 2021-05-13_Fair Saturday
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2021-05-13T07:50:01.150Z
modified: 2021-05-13T15:19:21.211Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/2021-05-13_Fair Saturday
id: 1gDmwptB7Y9jECl8wW6Q-k5u8HBSwOhCRUp6dDcOYNYc
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gDmwptB7Y9jECl8wW6Q-k5u8HBSwOhCRUp6dDcOYNYc/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

The document discusses the challenges and necessity of transforming culture, emphasizing that while culture is often resistant to change due to its historical roots, creativity and innovation are essential for progress. It highlights the exhaustion faced by creatives due to societal inertia and the importance of embracing change to challenge the status quo. The text identifies three forces aiding cultural transformation: access to technology, global decentralization, and the democratization of creativity, illustrating how these elements are reshaping cultural production and distribution, and empowering artists through technology and decentralization.

**Key Concepts:**

- Cultural transformation and resistance
- Creativity and societal inertia
- Access to technology in cultural sectors
- Global decentralization
- Democratization of creativity
- Impact of technology on cultural production
- Blockchain technology in digital art ownership

### Full Content

﻿Fair Saturday


Transforming Culture


Transforming culture sounds so harmonious. Everything is in a flow. So why not culture? Transforming culture sounds like the natural thing that happens when you let things just be.
But culture often resists transformation. It is grounded in history, with gravitas and dignity. Why should it concern itself with change?
Every time someone is doing something new, there will be someone else who will ask: “But why”? That “why” is cruel. It puts the finger on the person who does something different. It calls out the person who is trying out something new. If you want to be accepted and sane, don’t try transformation.
The burden of proof is with those who seek change, not with those who wish to stay the same. Have you ever tried to change a school curriculum, or a law?
Perhaps that is why being creative is so exhausting. Why doing creative work literally wears you out. Why psychological health is so fragile for those who are top creatives.
It appears that our societies have perfected the defense against all those that seek change. Inertia is a strong force.
Granted: much of our world that is beautiful and good is grounded in the past. There are amazing works of art from the past, profound traditions and ancient knowledge and skills that are worth preserving. 
But our societies equally need the daredevils who are challenging the status quo. If we only concern ourselves with what we already know, what life would that be? We need those who seek out the borders, who venture to the places where it hurts. For it is only there that we are doing work that really matters.
The past year has been a terrible experience for many of us. We have lost loved ones, have been put out of work or had to change our way of life upside down. The future is still unclear for those working in the cultural sectors. Will audiences come back? Will people enjoy traveling again? Will there be money to support the arts?
While a lot of these questions seem challenging and inspiring fear more than excitement, I believe there are three major forces in our world right now that might help us in finding a new way forward:
Access to technology
Global decentralization
Democratization of creativity
Take for example the ready availability of technology to communicate, record, edit and live stream music, theater or opera. During the last year its immense power has been brought to everyone’s attention.
Cultural institutions that had not been working with these technologies faced a bitter reality because the learning curve was steep. Those who had been active in the space before saw a surge in interest like nothing else!
And once we got over the first excitement of producing and watching live streams, we also started to realize that our online audiences want something else from a digital experience than from a live event in the theater. New formats were developed and experiments popped up everywhere. From home concerts to dancing robots in VR, this transformation of culture through technology has created entirely new formats and will continue to inspire new audiences and artists alike.
Self-producing content has also moved away the focus from traditional producers and distributors to ad-hoc networks and informal exchanges of artists and audiences. Often this resulted in cutting-out the man-in-the middle and therefore increasing the bottom line for the artists. Take for example the New York based jazz pianist Dan Tepfer, who, like many other artists, started their own concert series, often combining their solo performances with guests in other places. Everyone, including audiences joining in via zoom or youtube. The amazing part: setting up a system for charging tickets to a global audience is a matter of hours and proceeds flow to the artists directly.
More recently, digital artworks have been sold to the tune of 60+ Mio Dollars. Previously, these digitals images wore basically worthless, because why would I buy a file that can be copied by anyone and therefore be in their possession as well? But today, thanks to blockchain technology, an “official owner” of the artwork can be registered and that record cannot be falsified, tempered with or forged. There can still be copies of digital art, for sure, but there will only be one official owner registered on the blockchain.
In both of these examples, a tendency away from central authorities towards decentralization is present. Imagine what this development will allow artists to do who are currently struggling with censorship or exploitation!
Finally, I believe that in the past year we have seen the beginning of a new movement in thinking about creativity. More and more people are discovering their own creativity, are acknowledging that they are inherently creative. Just by having to deal with the crisis, each and everyone of us realized the power of their creativity on a daily basis. And politicians, business leaders and educators are taking note of it as well. Without creative humans, there will be no innovation, no prosperity and ultimately also no transformation of our culture!


---

## Ideen und Kommentare zu Sedas Artikel für Springer Nature

### Metadata

```yaml
title: Ideen und Kommentare zu Sedas Artikel für Springer Nature
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2020-10-31T10:21:18.304Z
modified: 2020-10-31T10:28:19.754Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/Ideen und Kommentare zu Sedas Artikel für Springer Nature
id: 1JFLrTfWU5rqdw-EfwlDgou5cjOdTLDKdxNIDeEhxXwg
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1JFLrTfWU5rqdw-EfwlDgou5cjOdTLDKdxNIDeEhxXwg/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

Research indicates that the success or failure of intrapreneurship heavily relies on the support from supervisors. This support can be structural, involving resources and decision-making freedom, or protective, offering a safeguard against the consequences of failure. The role of creativity in this context is questioned, particularly how it is integrated into the economic process. The concept of a patron, similar to a market-maker in the art world, is suggested as a model for fostering innovation by creating independent business units that succeed in the open market.

**Key Concepts:**

- Intrapreneurship success factors
- Supervisor support
- Structural vs. protective support
- Creativity in economic processes
- Role of a patron in innovation
- Independent business units
- Market success of innovation

### Full Content

﻿Die bisherige Forschung zeigt, dass für das Scheitern oder den Erfolg von Intrapreneurship der Faktor “Rückhalt durch Vorgesetzte” von großer Bedeutung ist.


Doch welcher Aspekt des Rückhalts ist hier gemeint?


Rückhalt kann einerseits strukturell sein, also im Sinne von Resourcen und Entscheidungsfreiheit, Budgets etc.


Rückhalt kann aber auch bedeuten Schutz vor Konsequenzen bei Mißerfolgen oder anderen Problemen.


Welche dieser Faktoren spielt bei der Förderung von Kreativität eine Rolle?


Ausserdem: Wie steht es mit der Einbettung von Kreativität in den wirtschaftlichen Prozess? Hat der Mäzen nicht auch in gewisserweise diese Rolle zu erfüllen?


Ein Beispiel wäre vielleicht Dakis, der ja nicht nur Kunst kauft, sondern auch so etwas wie ein Market-Maker ist. Er präsentiert Künstler und bringt sie in Museen. Dadurch steigt der Wert ihrer Kunst.


Übertragen auf Intrapreneurship wäre dies das Ausgliedern der Innovation in eine eigenständige geschäftliche Einheit und der Erfolg dieser Einheit im freien Markt.


---

## Creativity Matters

### Metadata

```yaml
title: Creativity Matters
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2020-08-08T12:14:04.344Z
modified: 2020-09-02T07:37:54.222Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/Creativity Matters
id: 1hpW5vzlktRA6wTFOQ-v0wFcOe9yngdXfgyiW8NXSemA
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1hpW5vzlktRA6wTFOQ-v0wFcOe9yngdXfgyiW8NXSemA/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

The document emphasizes the importance of creativity and implementation over mere execution in achieving success. The author shares personal experiences in both the arts and computer programming, highlighting how creativity can be harnessed through technology to bring ideas to life. The narrative underscores the transformative power of combining creativity with systematic implementation, suggesting that automating execution can free individuals to focus on innovation. The text argues that modern management should prioritize creative process-thinking over repetitive tasks, which can lead to greater satisfaction and innovation.

**Key Concepts:**

- Creativity and implementation
- Automation of execution
- Systematic process-thinking
- Transformative power of technology
- Innovation in management
- Combining arts and technology
- Liberation from repetitive tasks

### Full Content

```
﻿Why Creativity & Implementation Eat Execution for Breakfast 
Matthias Röder, Karajan Institute & Sonophilia Foundation
All my life, I have practiced creativity in one form or another. I started to play the classical guitar when I was five years old. Having become quite proficient early on, I added piano, drums, and music theory to my repertoire. Also, I wrote poems, invented games, directed plays, and much more. By all definitions, I was a creative person. 


My most profound personal experience with creativity came, however in a field far away from the arts: computer programming! I was already invested in my studies at the Mozarteum University in Salzburg when I bought my first computer at age twenty. At the time, I had been friends with a few computer whizzes and had spent quite a bit of time learning about operating systems and networks from them. This was around 1997 when the internet was already around, but not everyone had an email address or a fast internet connection at home. 


With my first computer, I now had the chance to get to the next level and go much deeper with the technology that I found so fascinating. I threw out the Windows 95 operating system that came with the computer and installed a fresh copy of Suse Linux. My computer looked more like a brick than a laptop. Without much processing power, I had to limit myself to using only the command line - no windows or mouse to play around with! Indeed, I had my computer, but what on earth should I do with it? 


I realized that if I knew how to program myself, I could make the computer do things exactly as I needed them. For instance, I’d always wanted to have a database for my poems that I could use to trigger new poems. With this database, I wanted to retrieve random combinations of words from the texts to trigger my imagination, then write a line of poetry to create new poems and feed those back into the database. There simply was no program that could do what I wanted, and so I decided that I would teach myself how to program and just do it! 


I cannot describe how hard this exercise was for me. I had a good understanding of what the program should do, but I struggled to systemize all of the little actions and orchestrate it into a functioning program. Getting the grammar and syntax of the programming language right was a massive challenge in itself, not to mention all of the typing mistakes that crashed the program before it even started. I had nightmares of computer bugs and fatal errors! In the mornings, I would wake up, tired already and crawl up in front of the computer. It felt like torture: lack of sleep, too much coffee, and little fresh air. 


In agony, I turned to my online heroes in the #linux channel on the Internet Relay Chat, a precursor of Skype and Whatsapp, and asked for help! It turned out that organizing computer programs into reusable functions and classes was very different from the kind of thinking I’d learnt as an artist. For the latter, I was much more focused on the result of the work I did. In computer programming, however, the question of how we get there is, at the very least, equally important. If you do not strive for efficiency, your program will be slow and will eventually become unresponsive. Once I got the hang of it, my program became much better, and to my great surprise, the problems disappeared gradually. 


I vividly remember the moment when the last bug was fixed, and for the first time, the program ran without any errors or crashes! It was late at night when I ran the command to start the program, saw the database queries. The inspiration terms came in, and I was prompted for my creative input. I typed something nonsensical to test the input mechanism and BANG! “Poetic Input Saved” WOW! It worked!!! The feeling of accomplishment was so profound. I had never felt so powerful before as at that moment. With that creative power emanating from my fingertips, I felt like a little god. It is only a slight exaggeration. 


For days, I rode the high. I felt like nothing could stand in my way! It was a pivotal moment in my life. From that day on, I kept using technology to turn my ideas into reality. My next projects revolved around musicology and databases, followed by a fascination with machine learning, all the way to using artificial intelligence to help finish Beethoven’s 10th Symphony. The transformative power of technology combined with creativity has been an essential catalyst in my life. However, it took me many years to understand why the moment of successfully finishing that first computer program was so impactful.


When I look at much of the work we do in our world today, I cannot help but see that we put a lot of effort, energy and time into doing repetitive tasks that numb us. If we are honest with ourselves, we have to admit we are stuck in an endless loop of execution. We are task-masters. To be fair, it feels good to tick the boxes on a checklist. It is satisfying to scan that pile of papers, to enter those receipts into the accounting system, or send out those invoices. But being stuck in an endless work loop does not create new products or services, nor does it develop your business. Ultimately, it does not make you happy. Ideally, you want to be involved in the part that comes before the work loop. It is the part where you develop an idea, where you invent, where you are creative.


Typically, what happens when people have a new idea is that they end up having more execution work than they had before. This is the reason why, in many organizations, most employees and managers are fighting against new ideas and projects. They intuitively know that the new idea is just adding to their workload. Imagine how many cool ideas are put to rest before they were even born!


But what if we could automate execution, or where that is not possible, outsource it? Would that not be a gamechanger? If we could focus on creating, and then create more? This is, of course, not a new idea. The difficulty with this approach is that you can only automate or outsource tasks and processes when you have defined them well enough. And this is where most of us make a critical mistake: Leaving the idea and the creative thought without a systematic description of its underlying processes, cuts off creativity’s lifeline. A creative idea without a sense of how to implement it is useless. 


Creativity needs automation and systematization. For every idea we create, we have to define how it can be automated. This is precisely what I had to do twenty-three years ago when I turned the idea for a creativity-boosting, poetry-inspiration machine into a workable computer program. The functions of the computer program were the systematic description of all of the processes necessary to automate its execution. After having completed the implementation of the idea, all execution was done entirely by the machine. Imagine that for every idea you have, you spend some extra time defining how it can be implemented in an automated fashion. You would save tremendous time and could immediately move on to your next big idea.


The focus on execution in modern management theory is a fetish of industrial age thinking, namely that getting things done is the epitome of human success. What we should focus on instead is creation and process-thinking so that execution can be done in an automated fashion. This kind of thinking will not only enable and liberate the small business owners and entrepreneurs but will also fuel a new area of creativity and innovation. 


And it may just give YOU the feeling of being a little god yourself.
```


---

