## Bringing the Karajan Music Tech Conference Online

### Metadata

```yaml
title: Bringing the Karajan Music Tech Conference Online
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2020-04-20T09:45:23.441Z
modified: 2020-04-28T15:18:56.544Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/Bringing the Karajan Music Tech Conference Online
id: 1jmRdUor5ipCXNhP7DxbtmKZI6RWW2eqP-FluFYyp-SE
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1jmRdUor5ipCXNhP7DxbtmKZI6RWW2eqP-FluFYyp-SE/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

The Karajan Music Tech Conference successfully transitioned to an online format due to COVID-19, resulting in a larger global audience and increased engagement. The virtual event, organized by the Eliette and Herbert von Karajan Institute in partnership with Volkswagen, highlighted the adaptability of humans and the relevance of technology in connecting people. Key strategies included using Zoom and Slack for interaction, conducting pre-conference interviews, and maintaining engagement through daily updates. The online format offered efficiency benefits and practical insights for future virtual events, such as the importance of practice sessions and using branded backgrounds.

**Key Concepts:**

- Virtual conference adaptation
- Global audience engagement
- Technology and human connection
- Interactive online platforms (Zoom, Slack)
- Pre-conference content creation
- Efficiency of online events
- Practical tips for virtual conferences

### Full Content

﻿I will admit, I didn’t expect to thrive while staying at home these last few weeks, especially when I considered the possibility that the Karajan Music Tech Conference would have to be postponed, or worse, cancelled altogether. Thankfully, we had a solid virtual mechanism put in place that made for a surprisingly successful alternative. We opted to take the Karajan Music Tech Conference online, a move which allowed for a much larger audience to experience the event, bringing visitors from 70 countries and ten times more visitors than in the real world! It also brought a new community of over 300 music technology entrepreneurs and scientists, as well as a wider brand recognition on social media.
 
The international shutdown due to COVID19 has undoubtedly cast some uncertainty for the future, but in many cases, it’s opened a world of possibilities and implications for the digital era. Organized by the Eliette and Herbert von Karajan Institute and in partnership with Volkswagen Aktiengesellschaft, the Karajan Music Tech Conference is an annual event that usually takes place in Salzburg. This year, the event was rolled out online on April 3, 2020, which, to me, shed some interesting light on how humans adapt and how we can embrace technology and AI, making this year’s topic—The Human Side of Technology—all the more relevant.
 
The necessity to bring the Karajan Music Tech Conference online began as just that—a necessity—but it quickly brought to my attention some key advantages of having an online platform. It was, first and foremost, built around interaction and the sharing of ideas and insights. People attend real-world conferences for inspiration through talks and panels, but seeing old friends and meeting new people creates new opportunities and provides momentum for each attendee. We used Zoom webinar technology for interaction between speakers and audiences and built a dedicated Slack workspace for people to interact and showcase their products and ideas. Enabling video conferencing on Slack for conference attendees allowed for small group and one-on-one interactions. We explored virtual reality platforms such as AltspaceVR, but found that only a small section of our audience used it. Instead, we had an interactive virtual conference dinner that brought people together in a fun and relaxing way!
 
Through this online mechanism, we aimed to create content to build anticipation and engage the community beyond the day of the conference. Attending a real world conference is a bit like a ritual. You prepare your speech or presentation, pack your suitcase, and set up meetings with friends and business partners. You then travel to the event’s location in person. All of this creates excitement and momentum, but the question is: how can you create the same effect for attendees of an online conference? By conducting interviews and showcasing videos for speakers ahead of the conference, interest around topics began to form. We invited registered participants to join our Telegroup and socialize. Finally, we sent updates on our progress on a daily basis—often as video messages—giving the team an opportunity to connect with participants.
 
As a result of this virtual version of the annual Karajan Music Tech Conference, I came up with some key takeaways and practical tips for similar future events. For one, everything takes less time online than in the real world. Think about it: no walking towards stage, no microphone hand-over, no water glass exchanges. For instance, we were done with welcome notes in 15 minutes as opposed to the usual 30 minutes! Utilizing a webinar software also helps create a stage and allow for discussion that requires several moderators. You should also create branded background images for the speakers to use in the Zoom call, and insist on people using their real names for Slack and Zoom calls; this will help to create a trusted environment. Practice sessions with speakers are essential! Your team can tutor them on how to use the technology efficiently. Finally, if you want to live stream to more than just your own website, you should create one official stream that can be sent to Facebook, Youtube, Twitter, or anywhere else you wish.


---

