## ArticleBoghossian

### Metadata

```yaml
title: ArticleBoghossian
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2019-11-18T12:44:16.689Z
modified: 2019-11-18T12:44:18.511Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/ArticleBoghossian
id: 1KoV-UR80Ninc3zaYxjBWwuWjej_M1TKADtJhCMphD58
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1KoV-UR80Ninc3zaYxjBWwuWjej_M1TKADtJhCMphD58/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

The article by Matthias Röder explores the role of artificial intelligence in music, emphasizing that these technologies enhance rather than replace human creativity. Röder draws examples from both classical and popular music to support his argument. He highlights the impact of AI on music composition, performance, and perception, making the topic accessible without requiring deep computer science knowledge. Röder, an expert in intellectual property and innovation management, has a significant background in music and technology, having founded the Karajan Music Tech Conference and Classical Music Hack Day series.

**Key Concepts:**

- Artificial intelligence in music
- Augmentation of human creativity
- Impact on music composition and performance
- Role of technology in music perception
- Interdisciplinary approach to music and technology

### Full Content

﻿Augmenting Musical Intelligence: How Technology has an Impact on the Composition, Performance and Perception of Music.


By Matthias Röder, PhD (Harvard ‘10)


In this article I provide a basic overview on the current state of artificial intelligence technologies and how they are applied in music. I argue that these technologies augment rather than supersede human creativity in music. The examples for my argument are drawn from classical and popular music alike. While the topic concerns advanced technologies, no deep understanding of computer science is required to follow my reasoning.


Max 5,000 words


Matthias Röder is an expert on intellectual property and innovation management. He holds a PhD in music from Harvard University and is an alumnus of the Mozarteum University Salzburg. Matthias currently serves as a board member of the Karajan Foundation. He is the Managing Director of the Eliette and Herbert von Karajan Institute as well as the CEO of Karajan Cinema Classics. In 2017, Matthias founded the Karajan Music Tech Conference, a cross-industry event to promote breakthrough technologies in music, media and audio. He is also the founder of the Classical Music Hack Day series which he launched in 2013. Matthias has won numerous prizes and accolades for his work, including most recently, the “Game Changer” Award of the Chamber of Commerce Salzburg. He is a sought-after speaker and lecturer who has taught at Harvard University, the Change & Innovation Management Program at University of St. Gall, and Salzburg University.


