## Kowledge Age and Networks

### Metadata

```yaml
title: Kowledge Age and Networks
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2019-09-01T08:54:31.037Z
modified: 2019-09-01T09:02:25.577Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/Kowledge Age and Networks
id: 16Msxm7cfHHAUig9y4r0VhB_tRWTCRp24P7XA_MHa3nM
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/16Msxm7cfHHAUig9y4r0VhB_tRWTCRp24P7XA_MHa3nM/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

Albert Wenger's book discusses the significant societal shift towards the Knowledge Age, likening it to past transitions such as the agrarian and industrial revolutions. He suggests that we are on the brink of a new era where the full potential is not yet visible, akin to an event horizon. The Knowledge Age promises a future where knowledge can be efficiently shared globally, allowing solutions to be universally accessible and problems to be solved once for all.

**Key Concepts:**

- Knowledge Age
- Non-linearity in societal shifts
- Global value networks
- Event horizon
- Efficient knowledge sharing
- Universal problem-solving

### Full Content

﻿Here is a very interesting book by VC Albert Wenger, discussing the general shift that our societies are in. According to his train of thought we are currently in a non-linearity comparable to those that we saw in the transformation to agrarian and later industrial ages. According to Wenger, today, we are moving towards the Knowledge Age. As in each non linearity before, what happens is that we can not fully see the possibilities of the Age that is coming (our fellow Sonophilian Andy Zmolek has called this the event horizon). Right now we only beginning to see the possibilities of the Knowledge Age. Imagine what will be possible if every piece of knowledge can efficiently shared across global value networks. Imagine we would have to solve every problem only once and that the solution will im immediately be available to everyone on the planet.This is precisely what matters.global is about.


