## Why we started The Mindshift

### Metadata

```yaml
title: Why we started The Mindshift
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2019-03-14T09:39:12.816Z
modified: 2019-06-26T11:10:30.741Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/Why we started The Mindshift
id: 1EdLK0b-q57o3tkzVOuEKEiJE1ROha-BOpzK7IGBwvlQ
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1EdLK0b-q57o3tkzVOuEKEiJE1ROha-BOpzK7IGBwvlQ/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

The Mindshift was founded on the belief that creativity is the driving force behind all innovation, especially as humanity transitions into a post-industrial world dominated by automation, AI, and decentralized computing. This shift heralds the Creative Age, where self-actualization and creativity outweigh traditional measures of work like speed and accuracy. To thrive in this new era, businesses must adapt by fostering creativity and updating outdated systems in education, health, and the economy. The Mindshift aims to guide individuals and organizations through these changes by promoting sustainable innovation strategies that unleash dormant creativity.

**Key Concepts:**

- Creativity as the driver of innovation
- Transition to a post-industrial world
- The Creative Age and self-actualization
- Challenges of adapting to new economic realities
- Importance of updating educational, health, and economic systems
- Human and machine collaboration
- Sustainable innovation strategies

### Full Content

```
﻿“Creativity drives all innovation”. 


If any phrase encompasses precisely why we started The Mindshift, this would be it. 


Humanity is rapidly moving towards a post-industrial world in which automation, artificial intelligence and decentralized computing are dominant. Such factors are also accelerating the emergence of a new kind of economy.


Once we began objectively looking at the world around us and what makes the average human in the 21st century tick, it became glaringly evident that as intelligent machines and algorithms take over many mundane and extraordinary tasks formerly executed by humans, we are facing a peculiarly wonderful challenge: to enhance people’s understanding of creativity and its potential in our lives. No longer does speed or accuracy define our work; rather, creativity is what really matters.


This is the dawning of a new era, one which we like to call The Creative Age because the people’s urge for self-actualization is greater than their desire for monetary compensation. This makes it quite difficult for companies to find and keep talent if they remain in the former mindset. We at The Mindshift want to bring forth a more substantial way of managing companies, preceded by a creative passion to find revolutionary ways of thinking and doing. The Creative Age is all about experimenting with the new, attempting what was once considered impossible and endeavoring to do it through ever-changing configurations of human and machine collaborators.


Unfortunately, such change towards The Creative Age is not as simple nor as playful as it seems, and it certainly doesn’t come without its setbacks. There’s a lot to consider in the way of maintaining and improving the way companies and sectors function. If we want to keep the levels of prosperity we’ve managed to attain thus far, we must be diligent in updating our outdated educational, health, and economic systems. Failure to do so would be a fatal blow to our economy, which would in turn, undo the progress of our companies, markets, and societies in general. 


The Mindshift is here to help forge a path through these turbulent times. Our goal is to guide you towards a sustainable innovation strategy, and in our view, this starts with unleashing the creativity that may lie dormant in each and every individual and offering them the push they need to move forward.


Why we started The Mindshift
* humanity is quickly moving into a post industrial world
* automation, artificial intelligence and decentralized computing are accelerating the emergence of a new kind of economy 
* as intelligent machines and algorithms take over many tasks formerly executed by humans, we are facing a wonderful and peculiar challenge
* no longer does the speed or accuracy with which we do our work matter
instead, it is our creativity that matters most since creativity is what drives all innovation.
* to us it is clear that we are seeing the dawn of a new age. We are calling it the creative age defined by the people’s urge for self-actualization (which makes it very difficult for companies to find and keep talent)
* The creative age is all about doing the new, trying out what was impossible before and doing it in ever changing configurations of human and machine collaborators.
* But the change towards the creative age is not as simple and playful as it seems. 
* If we want to keep our levels of prosperity we will need to work hard to update our outdated educational, health, and economic systems
* If we fail to succeed, fatal blows to our economy will undo our companies, markets and societies
* The Mindshift is there to help find a path in these turbulent times. Our goal is to guide you towards a sustainable innovation strategy. And in our view this starts with unleashing the creativity of each and everyone in our creative age.
```


---

## A Couple of Take-Homes from the Sonophilia Embassy in Düsseldorf

### Metadata

```yaml
title: A Couple of Take-Homes from the Sonophilia Embassy in Düsseldorf
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2019-06-10T15:58:53.209Z
modified: 2019-06-10T16:19:41.559Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/A Couple of Take-Homes from the Sonophilia Embassy in Düsseldorf
id: 1-UO6_WQZA2bZ-7HDIWx4zvxsj7E3ZLXtPzrl_v_dnyE
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1-UO6_WQZA2bZ-7HDIWx4zvxsj7E3ZLXtPzrl_v_dnyE/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

During discussions with thought leaders, several key issues were highlighted. Digital artists feel underrepresented by museums and collectors, and there is a call for more support in this area. In the realm of autonomous driving, engineers express skepticism about Stage 3, suggesting a direct leap to Stage 4 might be more feasible. Payment solutions remain a significant challenge for Chinese tourists in the West and vice versa, due to incompatible systems. Additionally, toxic corporate cultures continue to drive talented individuals away, raising questions about the importance of integrity in leadership roles.

**Key Concepts:**

- Support for digital artists
- Skepticism about autonomous driving Stage 3
- Challenges in international payment solutions
- Toxic corporate culture
- Importance of integrity in leadership

### Full Content

﻿Over the weekend I had the privilege to speak to a few a thought leaders about various topics. Here are my take-home messages:


1. Artists who work in digital believe that museums and collectors should do more to support and represent this important movement in art. I am so grateful that I have met Roman Lispksi, Christiana Berlina and Tim Berresheim to continue the dialogue in this arena.
2. Autonomous driving Stage 3 is the one that engineers are most sceptical of. It requires humans to observe the road at all times to interact with the driving AI. Engineers believe that it will be better to jump to stage 4 directly (only AI and only on controlled environments)
3. Payment solution experiences for tourists coming from China visting “the west” as well for foreigners visiting still suck mayor time. No one accepts wechat pay, alipay in the west. Cash and European debit cards are not accepted over there. Credit cards are too expensive.
4. Assholes in corporate culture (even the family-owned ones) are still driving amazing people out of the organization, much to the detriment of shareholders. When will personal integrity and maturity become a criterion for hiring top executives?


