## Why the music business is dead, and a computational understanding of music is the way out

### Metadata

```yaml
title: Why the music business is dead, and a computational understanding of music is the way out
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2019-05-20T07:15:06.698Z
modified: 2019-05-20T13:01:55.922Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/Why the music business is dead, and a computational understanding of music is the way out
id: 1HOBiPPyj-oDL_EBa5tCqnK4JTpxoBQitJaMICukTuLE
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1HOBiPPyj-oDL_EBa5tCqnK4JTpxoBQitJaMICukTuLE/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

The document discusses the evolving music market, emphasizing the decline in profit margins for digital content usage and the strategies companies are employing to counteract revenue loss. It highlights the importance of contextualizing digital content and leveraging data to add value, alongside the growing significance of interactive and co-created content. The music industry is moving towards efficiency, affecting both businesses and artists differently, with businesses focusing on scale and artists on brand monetization and fan interaction. New opportunities arise from computational approaches, such as gamification of music education, personalized sound experiences, and AI-enhanced creative tools.

**Key Concepts:**

- Decline in digital content profit margins
- Contextualization and data-driven value in music
- Efficiency in the music industry
- Business and artist strategies for revenue loss
- Computational approaches in music
- Interactive and co-created content
- New opportunities in music education and AI tools

### Full Content

﻿My talk gives an overview on the development of the market for music, highlighting the deterioration of margins for usage of content in the digital space. What are some strategies that companies are developing to deal with this massive loss of revenue? How are consumers reacting to these developments? I argue that the contextualization of digital content as well as the usage of information derived from the content directly might provide additional value to stakeholders. Going forward I see an increased importance for interaction with content, as we can see from video games, as well as co-creation and open art forms.


1. What is the Karajan Institute?
   1. Continuing the legacy of Herbert von Karajan to bring music to as many people as possible
   2. Primary income stream: Management of copyrights
2. The question that some of you will doubtlessly have: Why does the managing director of a large musical estate care for Music Information Retrieval or computational musicology?
3. Of course, it has to do with my personal interest. Who I am and what I care about.
4. Macro trends of our world:
   1. Increase of automation effectiveness in most areas of industries
   2. Decentralization of information, tools and value across the globe
   3. Increasing speed of innovation cycles
   4. More need for fast innovation in all areas (competition has capabilities quickly after initial publication)
   5. Therefore need for more creativity in business, science and society.
5. Two things I would like everyone to understand about the music industry:
   1. The music market is quickly moving towards maximum efficiency.
   2. This has huge implications for both businesses and artists, but the consequences and strategies of dealing with the situation are also hugely different between these two.
6. Examples for increasing efficiency in music market:
   1. Increased information availability for creative process
   2. Sinking production cost
   3. White label solutions for products
   4. Abundant options for outsourcing of services
   5. Low barrier of entry for supply chain (think CD Baby and Discmakers)
   6. Streaming services (direct content delivery into the ears of consumers)
7. What this means for businesses (labels and publishers):
   1. Prices for music consumption are falling
   2. Pressure on cost to come down
   3. As margins shrink, scale becomes paramount
8. How business are responding:
   1. Fight tech-companies by lobbying and sueing (YouTube)
   2. Build larger catalogues so that chances for super-hits increase
   3. Spend marketing dollars only on “trending” artists (data science)
   4. License to as many services as possible
   5. Request upfront licensing cost from all services
   6. Optimize royalty payments (“screw artists”)
   7. Create more and more product configurations to address myriad of customer interests (playlisting)
   8. Follow-up hits with style copies (ever wondered why everything in the top ten sounds alike?)
9. What this means for artists (bands, musicians, composers, lyricists):
   1. Niches are as (un)lucrative as is main stream
   2. Live business is growing in importance
   3. Monetization of artist brand is more important
   4. Direct interaction with fans is crucial
10. How artists are responding:
   1. Music as a hobby
   2. Pooling of artists’ fan bases (surge in covers)
   3. More touring and more meet n greet etc.
   4. Increasing their social media time
   5. Diversifying of activities (side projects, aliases for more service-like artist production)
11. How computational approach can help:
   1. Squeezing last drops out of dying system by automation, playlist generation, suggestions and data science.
   2. CREATING NEW OPPORTUNITIES for people to composer, make and enjoy music, both on- and off-line (lowering the barrier of entry)
12. New opportunities for value creation in a post-industrial world
   1. Gamification of music education through intelligent musical instruments. Imagine a world in which every musical instrument is capable to understand exactly what is being played on it. Sensors in fretboards, bridges, mouth pieces and valves communicate in realtime with musical computers that analyse, compare, give feedback to the player. (Remember when you were a kid and had one lesson per week on Monday?)
   2. Adaptive and personalized sound in concert halls, clubs and other venues as well as in sound systems increases enjoyment of music for everyone. What was formerly a one to many connection where one piece of content was delivered to everyone in the same way, now increasingly becomes a “different” version to each individual.
   3. Individualized music medicine and health improvements. Which music should I play and listen to in order to improve my condition? Which interpretation might be best suited? Possible already today, but needs computational understanding of music to scale. (Altzheimer prevention)
   4. AI-enhanced creative tools in music production software (musical autocomplete, imrpovements for mixing) and mechanical instruments such as Yamaha disclavier (support and improvement of touch, timing, dynamics based on database of musical interpretations).
   5. Interactive music playback (conduct the recording)
   6. Enhanced scores for musicological purposes
   7. Visualizations for music
   8. Interactive holographic models of artists
   9. Artists providing optional content that is explorable


---

