## ThreeStrategiesToIncreaseDigitalCompetenciesInTeams

### Metadata

```yaml
title: ThreeStrategiesToIncreaseDigitalCompetenciesInTeams
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2018-07-11T12:16:40.744Z
modified: 2018-07-12T06:54:46.483Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/ThreeStrategiesToIncreaseDigitalCompetenciesInTeams
id: 12HeHD_lUoAcELncWzSMdt3TmXVtbL0mzlrxCkY3toLQ
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/12HeHD_lUoAcELncWzSMdt3TmXVtbL0mzlrxCkY3toLQ/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

Digital transformation is essential for small and medium enterprises to stay competitive, but many projects fail due to poor management and lack of enthusiasm. To enhance digital competency, three strategies are recommended: building an internal digital community to facilitate learning and support, encouraging experimentation by providing resources and opportunities for trying new tools, and integrating management with development/IT teams to foster collaboration and understanding. These strategies aim to create an eager-to-learn mindset and overcome resistance to change.

**Key Concepts:**

- Digital transformation
- Internal digital community
- Encouraging experimentation
- Integration of management and IT teams
- Eager-to-learn mindset
- Overcoming resistance to change
- Collaboration and understanding

### Full Content

﻿Three Strategies to Increase Digital Competency in Teams


Many small and medium enterprises today have to go through a digital transformation in order to remain competitive or to redefine their business models. However we keep hearing that those transformation projects fail due to poor management. Because in most cases managers forget to create a playful environment and excitement around their transformation efforts. The management style and strategy are indeed the most important key stone when managing digitization. Establishing an eager-to-learn mindset can be challenging in cases where teams have been around for a while and, more crucially, sceptical towards change. Here are three management strategies that have proven useful for us in various projects in incentivizing team members to build and increase digital competency.


1. Build an internal digital community. Analog teams that are confronted with digitalization topics face many hurdles. In some ways this process is like learning a new language. Make sure that your team knows who to turn to with questions and issues. Ideally, you can set up a chat group to address these issues for the whole group. Great tools for community support are slack, telegram or even facebook groups. Sometimes it might be useful for team members to ask questions one-on-one. Integrate time for questions and sharing of learning in your weekly team meetings. Encourage everyone to share their insights and never forget to distinguish those who are brave enough to ask questions!
2. Encourage and reward experimentation. Trying out new tools and applying newly acquired skills are powerful motivators. They tap into two of our basic drives: curiosity and creativity. Make sure to provide team members with a budget to try out new services or platforms for digital management and productivity. Following the principle of „perfect is the enemy of done“ will free your team from preferring the status quo over the potential benefits of change. Finally, try out new formats for working together, such as company-wide hackathons, design-thinking workshops or simply making time for individual micro projects.
3. Integrate management and development/IT teams. This is the most fundamental change and if implemented well, you create fast learning digital teams in no time. For it to be successful, members from both teams must be working on the project together, forming a close bond and association. Whenever possible, do not rely on agencies or outside consultants, unless you are willing to work closely and fully integrated in your team. Make sure that every aspect of the project can be understood in basic terms by everyone involved. Technological discussions should always be framed in general terms. Technical terminology needs to be explained carefully and great emphasis should be put on making sure that everyone is on the same page. From our experience, this is the single most important driver for forming a digital mindset in the team.


---

## Salzburg Talk

### Metadata

```yaml
title: Salzburg Talk
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2018-06-21T06:55:48.279Z
modified: 2018-06-30T22:08:14.144Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/Salzburg Talk
id: 1PAU1jn67i67uENiauazDYkQ-SKSiGB8Wm-YzNy6YPb4
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1PAU1jn67i67uENiauazDYkQ-SKSiGB8Wm-YzNy6YPb4/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

The document is a speech focusing on the importance of creativity as a fundamental component of innovation, challenging common myths about creativity being an innate or exclusive trait. The speaker emphasizes that creativity is a learnable and reproducible process, not confined to the arts, and should be democratized to leverage the potential of every individual. The speech also explores the impact of AI on creativity, suggesting that while machines can be trained to be creative, the philosophical question remains whether they should be. The speaker advocates for nurturing creativity in business by fostering environments that encourage experimentation, stepping out of comfort zones, and valuing diverse perspectives.

**Key Concepts:**

- Creativity as a learnable process
- Impact of AI on creativity
- Democratization of creativity
- Challenging myths about creativity
- Creativity in business and innovation
- Importance of diverse perspectives
- Encouraging experimentation and play

### Full Content

```
﻿Thank you very much for this nice intro. I feel very privileged to be here as a senior advisor to SC and to talk to you. This session here is different than what you’ve been doing in the rest of your days at the academy. We are not going to talk about business models or we’re not going to talk about go-to-market strategies. 


But we are going to talk about the most important pre-condition to make you and your companies great! We’re going to talk about that magical ingredient to be able to build disruptive products day in day out. 


So, we will deep dive into the art of innovation and talk CREATIVITY! In the next 30 or so minutes, I am going to take you to a journey into the essence of what creativity is and how to harness it in your own lives and help others do the same.


My talk is here to tickle your critical thinking and to bring in a fresh perspective into what many people assume to know about creativity.


But before anything else, we will do our traditional listening meditation to arrive here in this room and to open our minds to experience something unusual.


So please make yourselves comfortable in your seats...


Change your seat!


We’re going to take a long arch starting: 
* The impact of technology on creativity 
* We will break the myth of creativity
* You’ll hear some of my story 
* I will give you a couple of tips to unleash your everyday creativity
* Last but not least: there will be music, of course  


Human vs. Machine:


Let’s start with a short experiment: pls listen and look carefully.
What do these creative works have in common?


It’s probably not hard to guess, right? Yes, they are all produced, generated and/or performed by AI.


This crowd here for sure knows, that AI is already a part of our lives in many different areas. Probably in all of your startups, you use AI in one way or the other: data analysis, diagnostics. But AI is also quite common in more traditional industries with loads of reproducible, conveyor belt-like work. These are all things we’re already used to.


But how are we going to react, if AI suddenly also takes over art and creativity? Art and Creativity: The untouchable, last castles of the human soul...


But we would be naive to think, that arts and creativity would remain untouched. On the contrary, making a machine creative; this challenge of the impossible, is super attractive for AI researchers.


Some of you may remember the Go Game won by Googles Deepmind computer in 2016.


There were 2 groundbreaking moments in this achievement: 1) the computer was trained differently: After having reached a basic proficiency, it played against itself, and taught itself how to play. 2) It followed a different strategy: probability of winning, instead of elegantly maximising territory. Thus, in the real game against Lee Sudol, computer made moves that no one had expected. Moves that were considered tabu. But tabus didn’t itch the computer. 


This is a great learning, that shows us that we humans sometimes stand in our own way because of our tabus, rules or prejudices.


So let’s go back to art: in my opinion, the question whether a computer can be creative or not, is no longer a technical question but rather a philosophical one. Because technically, we will definitely get there.


However, the question, whether a computer should be creative or not, that question brings us into a new dimension.


Right now there’s lots of polemic discussion around this question. 


These examples here caused for instance caused a lot of speculation. Ahmed ElGammal at Rutgers University trained his AI with Masterworks of the last 500 years. But at the end, he didn’t want to just imitate styles, but he wanted his computer to come up with new pictures. Ultimately he came up with a model that worked like how art students learn. Look at masterworks, learn from their style, connect old with the new and iterate until something new emerges. This is exactly how the art studies work. 


Mr. Gammals pictures were then exhibited in Art Basel to see how people would react. People didn’t know the artist behind the pictures, but most of them liked them even better than the modern art hanging in Art Basel. When the visitors asked to describe the paintings, they used words like: inspiring, emotional. In the end they were asked, whether they’d believe that the artist was a computer; 85% said “no”. You can imagine what happened afterwards: they were shocked and disappointed.


Of course. 


The idea of the creative machine is for many frightening. But this fear should not come from the end-of-the-world scenarios some people spread. No. In my opinion, if we choose to be afraid, than we should be afraid for a much more profound reason: As humanity, we are standing at a turning point and probably for the first time history, we must seriously think about the relevance of our existence. The emergence of the creating machine, forces us to think about our superiority as a species. 


And this thought, makes a new definition of creativity inevitable. Creativity should no longer be confined and understood as an artistic work or genius invention. Instead, as the leaders of the future, we must democratize creativity! And understand creativity as the normal basis of our regular being. We no longer need to worship single geniuses, who show us their masterful skills. Instead, we need to think about how to scale creativity. Because we need the creative powers of every person to leap forward with our organisations, and as a species at large. 


But is everybody creative? I believe, inherently, yes. But I’ll get to that in a minute. But even if not, let me tell you, if we can manage to teach computers how to be creative, we sure can do the same for humans!


But for that, we need to disrupt the myths around creativity. And since, I myself some from arts, I think I am allowed :-)


The creativity myth:


I am a musician and a management consultant for creativity and innovation culture. I have also founded the creative leadership network Sonophilia. You can think of Sonophilia as a global think-tank with members from arts, sciences, top-managers of DAX and Fortune 500 companies, politicians and journalists. At Sonophilia people from all sorts of different backgrounds, come together under the motto of “innovation is applied creativity”, to exchange ideas, get new inspiration and develop creative solutions.


As someone who deals with creativity in so many different ways (as an artist and as an enabler of creativity in companies), let me tell you, that there’s almost no other realm in which people weave so many myths as in creativity. Mozart was touched by a divine hand, so that he could compose everything in one sitting, the lone genius Isaac Newton discovered his theory of gravity suddenly when he saw an apple fall from a tree, and so forth. So yes, both of these guys never had to work hard, they were just creative.


Myth 1: one is either creative or not.


People tell stories and make a mystery around creativity. They talk about divine sparks, flashes of genius and sudden inspirations. And if they want to be particularly rational, then they talk about genetic predisposition. But these stories are actually harmful. For two reasons: 1) they deny us our power to control our creativity, as if our body is a passive conductor that obeys the orders of some external, metaphysical force, and 2) they separate people into different classes; the ones that are creative and the ones that won’t be no matter how hard they tried. 


Therefore I am actually thankful for all the developments in computer technology that show that creativity is no wizardry but just a process.
I admit, it is a complex process, probably much more complex than any other process. But even so, it is still learnable and reproducible. 
Because it doesn’t happen somewhere between the earth and the heaven, but in our brains. And the brain is a plastic organ that is able to learn and remodel itself until the plug has been pulled off. 


What I am claiming here is not only my opinion, but also the opinion of the leading researchers in creativity studies and neurosciences. They have found that one neither needs to be highly intelligent nor the genetic predisposition is a guarantee for creativity. All that matters is how we nurture our brain to use its creativity. 


As long as the brain is in tact, every person is born into this world as a potential genius. Think about the children. We never have to tell a child, “now think out-of-the-box”, “be creative!”. We are made to be creative, everything is perfect, everything we need is there. 


CLICK: But when we grow up, we learn to fit. Our dreams become more tamed and we start to adjust them into the systems instead of changing the systems to help us dream even bigger. Through outside influences, we start developing an immense fear of failure, as if making a mistake is the worst thing that could happen. So, it seems better not to do anything than making a mistake or pissing our bosses off. 


For me it was also not much different. 


BACH.


Until 7 years ago, my life looked very much like this piece of music. It was super stable, predictable and I had my routines. I felt secure. Coming from a very chaotic country (Turkey), security was definitely what I wanted. Doing my concerts, teaching… Everything went according to plan. But the hamster wheel started to feel too small. Was it all? Was this going to be my life till the end? I had a feeling inside and the hope that the answer would be “No”.


Than I saw these words and realized that the real act of creativity is not necessarily an artistic act, but it starts much earlier in life. Imagine a world where people realize their power to shape their life...


Now I work with governments, individuals, companies to help them understand and use their creative potential. Their potential to imagine and shape the future they want to live in.


Myth 2: So if you still believe that creativity is related  only to arts, then come find me later and we will fight :-) 


Also in business life people want to be creative. A recent study shows that only 1 out of 4 people feel that they live up to their potential at workplace. This is not only sad for our resources but also expensive because people won’t feel engaged or motivated if they can’t shape!


The Global Workplace Engagement Studies of Gallup show that this so called “disengagement” costs approx. 275 Billion Euros in Germany per year - only due to absence! In the US this number is even higher.


But what is it that motivates people, what is the fuel that drives them? Well the answer comes from the Austrian Economist Joseph Schumpeter as early as 1911 in his book “the theory of economic development”. He says, that all positively motivated activity is driven by our joy in creative work.
He continues and compares the successful entrepreneurs to artists, who want to understand problems, love to experiment, want to expand their horizons and leave their mark in this world in form of change.


I think this is a very interesting and modern view, how he compares artists with business people and puts creativity in the middle as the common nominator. 
 
Because the reality looks different even in our modern times. Although we have o problems to talk about creativity when it comes to art, we are more careful using the word when we talk about business. Because creativity is elusive and hard to measure, at least with the tools most companies are using. Therefore it’s easier to talk about innovation: innovative products and business models. 


But in reality, it’s never the business models or the products that are innovative, but the people, mind’s behind them! It is our creativity that drives innovation: Our ability to imagine and build things. We shouldn’t be obsessed with KPIs and quarterly numbers so much. The history is full with examples that show that where creativity comes first, the right numbers will eventually follow. Here a quick view to such companies…


But these here show that if we want to remain in the innovation game, we must systematically nurture our creativity culture.


How?


1: Believe and Trust: these two are the absolut starting point. Let’s ignore everything we believed to know about creativity and start to trust in the creative potential in everyone (even in engineers!). Creativity is our factory setting, so to speak. But it works best and fastest when we build upon people’s strengths rather than on weaknesses. In this process, it’s very important to also fight against our egos and leave the driver's seat from time to time to make room for other ideas. I know it can be very difficult when you’re growing a company that’s your baby:-) I see in my work that one of the main parameters of great leadership is to set the stage for others to shine!


2: Get out of the comfort zone: Unlearn


“The real voyage of discovery consists not in seeking new landscapes, but in having new eyes” said Marcel Proust once. But this is not easy to do if we keep ourselves in the same circle with the same questions and people. Let me give you an example: one of my customers, a pretty big mobile company, that’s very much into mobile photography gave me a team and asked me to explore the trends in the future of mobile photography with them. I realized soon, that we started to circle around the same ideas over and over again. Making better cameras, better phones, displays etc. We were talking the future of mobile photography, but neither the future nor the mobile parts were giving me enough goosebumps. So I decided to bring in an outsider from iot and implants, and boom, both mobile and future got a whole different perspective.


Sometimes, you’re just too much in the thing. We’re in the business of building mobile phones, and not implants right? 


The american Designer Ralph Osterhout has a more practicable and cheap solution: every now and then he goes to a kiosk and buys random magazines, just to gain a new perspective and to see what moves other people. Here are some such examples. For this kind of perspective shift, I have founded Sonophilia, where top people from different backgrounds retreat for two days to exchange ideas.


3) Play & Experiment:


Did you know that humans are the only mammals that stop playing after having reached the adult age? Or maybe we should say: we do play games, but our games start to serve a different purpose; the purpose of winning. So we no longer play to experience something new and to learn, but to be confirmed in what we already know. 
When was the last time you said yes to something that didn’t seem to serve a concrete purpose? I know this sounds quite counter intuitive because we’re busy all the time, but practice saying yes if someone wants to play.


I got my aha moment, when my little girl reached the playing age. It was mind opening! To kids, it never matters what the original purpose of an object is. It can become anything! They just start playing with a simple question: what if? So I decided to treat daily objects as potential music instruments.


When I first started, it was a crazy project, and now my fans call me the piano hacker. So when you go back home, take the first object on the floor and think about 10 different contexts to use it including within the context of your own startup product. Don’t be afraid to be absurd, because don’t forget it’s all just a game!


Thank you!
```


---

## Blockchain Technology will Revolutionize the Music Business (and that is a good thing)

### Metadata

```yaml
title: Blockchain Technology will Revolutionize the Music Business (and that is a good thing)
type: application/vnd.google-apps.document
created: 2017-10-09T08:33:36.419Z
modified: 2018-05-11T06:09:27.115Z
path: /My Drive/My Texts / Presentations/#PUBLISHED_DONE/Blockchain Technology will Revolutionize the Music Business (and that is a good thing)
id: 1ijla1n3mkTJ_39wO47Z_WQvQjZZTW9u_4RN7rTfSbLI
url: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1ijla1n3mkTJ_39wO47Z_WQvQjZZTW9u_4RN7rTfSbLI/edit?usp=drivesdk
```

### Summary & Key Concepts

The document discusses two major issues in the music industry: inadequate artist remuneration in the digital streaming ecosystem and the lack of transparency in royalty accounting systems. It suggests that blockchain technology, smart contracts, and Token Generating Events could address these challenges by providing fair remuneration and transparency. The document highlights the importance of adopting new technologies to solve longstanding problems in the music industry and invites participation in the Karajan Music Tech Conference dedicated to these topics.

**Key Concepts:**

- Artist remuneration in digital streaming
- Intransparent royalty accounting systems
- Blockchain technology in music
- Smart contracts
- Token Generating Events (Initial Coin Offerings)
- Fair remuneration and transparency
- Karajan Music Tech Conference

### Full Content

﻿Speaking with many artists and music entrepreneurs all over the world, I hear two major threads that are coming up over and over again:


1) Artist remuneration in the new digital ecosystem is problematic. Streaming is becoming the predominant way to consume music, but royalty payouts are minimal and will not result in sustainable career paths for most artists.


2) The royalty accounting systems used by labels, publishers and digital platforms are highly intransparent. Royalty payments made cannot be easily verified by rights owners.


Blockchain technology will solve these issues for present future generations of artists. That is why we dedicate the next Karajan Music Tech Conference to blockchain, smart contracts and Token Generating Events (aka Initial Coin Offerings).


We are at a crucial turning point in history. Interest in fair remuneration and transparency is going mainstream. Under the pressure of regulators, the financial sector has to reinvent itself. The automotive industry is going through similar changes right now. In music we see organizations such as the Open Music Initiative or the Decentralized Music Foundation taking on (and solving!) decade-old problems.


Now is the time to fix our legacy systems and use available technologies to make it happen. Please join me in this effort, spread the word and register for our conference.


Thank you!


---

